'''Joseph Steve Sakic''' ({{IPAEng|<U+02C8>s<U+0251><U+02D0>k<U+0268>k}}<ref>Emrick, Mike (2002). [http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/shn/pronunc.htm NHL pronunciation guide]. Retrieved on [[2007-09-20]].</ref>) (born [[July 7]], [[1969]] in [[Burnaby, British Columbia|Burnaby]], [[British Columbia]]) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] professional ice hockey [[center (ice hockey)|center]] who has played his entire [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) career with the [[Quebec Nordiques]]/[[Colorado Avalanche]] franchise. In his 18-year tenure, Sakic has won the [[Stanley Cup]] twice, various NHL trophies and has been voted into 13 [[NHL All-Star Game]]s. He is regarded as one of the strongest team leaders to ever play in the league,<ref name="Rocky Mountain News"/> and has been able to motivate his team throughout his entire career to play at a winning level.<ref name="Canadian Gold">{{cite book | last = Podnieks | first = Andrew | title = Canadian Gold 2--2: Making Hockey History | year = 2002 | publisher = Fenn Publishing Company Ltd. | location = Bolton, Ontario | pages = 144}}</ref>

Over the course of his career, Sakic has been one of the most productive forwards in the game, having twice scored 50 goals and earning at least 100 points in six different seasons. His [[wrist shot (ice hockey)|wrist shot]], considered to be one of the best in the NHL, has been the source of much of his production.<ref name="TSN Bio">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?id=831&hubname=nhl-avalanche|title=Joe Sakic Statistics on TSN.ca|accessdate=2007-04-09|publisher=TSN.com|year=2007|author=TSN.com}}</ref> At the conclusion of the [[2006-07 NHL season|2006&ndash;07 NHL season]], he was the 9th all-time points leader in the NHL, as well as 14th in all-time goals<ref name="500 goals">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?articleid=343977&page=NewsPage&service=page|title=NHL 500-Goal Scorers |accessdate=2007-11-21|publisher=NHL.com|year=2007|author=Associated Press}}</ref> and 11th in all-time assists.<ref name="100 Points"/> During the [[2002 Winter Olympics]] in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]], Sakic helped lead [[Canadian national men's ice hockey team|Team Canada]] to its first gold medal in 50 years, and was voted as the tournament's most valuable player.<ref name="Canadian Gold"/> He has represented the team in six other international competitions, including the [[Canada at the 1998 Winter Olympics|1998]] and [[Canada at the 2006 Winter Olympics|2006]] Winter Olympics. After the [[2000-01 NHL season|2000&ndash;01 NHL season]], Sakic was named the MVP of the NHL by the [[Hart Memorial Trophy|hockey writers]] and his [[Lester B. Pearson Award|fellow players]].<ref name="Recordbook"/>


==Early life==
Sakic was born and raised in [[Burnaby, British Columbia|Burnaby]] to Marijan and Slavica Sakic<ref name="Encyclopedia">{{cite book 
| last = Francis 
| first = Daniel (Editor) 
| title = Encyclopedia of British Columbia 
| year = 2000 
| publisher = Harbour Publishing 
| location = Madeira Park, BC 
| id = ISBN 1-55017-200-X 
| pages = 806}}</ref> (originally <U+0160>aki<U+0107>, {{IPA2|<U+02C8><U+0283>aki<U+02A8>}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/sports/more/496937/index.do?show=all|title=Bilo kuda, Hrvati svuda|publisher=[[Ve<U+010D>ernji List]]|date=[[2006-06-08]]|author=Dra<U+017E>en Brajdi<U+0107>|accessdate=2007-09-20|language=Croatian}}</ref>), ethnic-[[Croats|Croatian]] immigrants from the former Yugoslavia.<ref name="GrowingUp"/> He did not learn to speak [[English language|English]] until [[kindergarten]], having been raised with [[Croatian language|Croatian]] as his [[mother-tongue]]. This language barrier would make him a demure, quiet individual later in life.<ref name="GrowingUp">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/columns/wigge/sakic033006.html|title=Powers far beyond mortal men|accessdate=2006-09-19|publisher=NHL.com|year=2006|author=Wigge, Larry}}</ref>  Growing up as the child of immigrants, Sakic was instilled with a strong work-ethic, a trait which would serve him well in his hockey career.<ref name="GrowingUp"/> As a smaller player, he was forced to use skill rather than size to excel, and modeled himself after his idol, [[Wayne Gretzky]].<ref name="No Average Joe"/> After showing exceptional promise as a young hockey player in Burnaby, Sakic was referenced as a new Wayne Gretzky in the making.<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> He scored 83 goals as part of 156 points, in only 80 games in Burnaby, and was added to the [[Lethbridge Broncos]] of the [[Western Hockey League]] for the last part of the [[1985-86 WHL season|1985&ndash;86 season]].<ref name="Legends of Hockey"/>

In [[1986-87 WHL season|1986&ndash;87]], the Broncos relocated to [[Swift Current, Saskatchewan]], becoming the [[Swift Current Broncos]]. Joe, playing in his first full season, was named Rookie of the Year of the WHL.<ref>{{cite web |title =Rookie of the Year - Jim Piggott Memorial Trophy|url =http://www.whl.ca/records/awards.php?id=55|publisher =[[Western Hockey League|WHL]]|accessdate =2007-09-18}}</ref> He notched 60 goals and 73 assists for 133 points. But while Sakic enjoyed success on the ice, his team faced a tragedy on the night of [[December 30]], [[1986]]. The Broncos were driving to a game against the [[Regina Pats]] and due to bad weather conditions, the driver lost control on a patch of black ice outside of Swift Current, and the bus crashed. While Sakic was unharmed, four of his teammates (Trent Kresse, Scott Kruger, Chris Mantyka, and Brent Ruff) were killed. This incident had a lasting impact on the young Sakic,<ref name="No Average Joe">{{Cite web
| url = http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?articleid=288049&page=NewsPage&service=page| title = No average Joe - Sakic quietly moving among NHL all-time greats men| accessdate = 2007-01-28| publisher = [[NHL|NHL.com]]| year = 2007| author = ''Canadian Press''}}</ref> who has declined to talk about the crash during his career.<ref name="Denial of Death">{{Cite web
| url = http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=swiftcurrent&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab1pos1
| title = Denial of Death
| accessdate = 2007-04-09
| publisher = ''ESPN''
| year =2007
| author = Joyce, Gare}}</ref> The next year, in [[1987-88 WHL season|1987&ndash;88]], Sakic was the WHL Most Valuable Player and [[CHL Player of the Year|Canadian Major Junior Player of the Year]] scoring 160 points (78 goals, 82 assists), tying him with [[Theoren Fleury]] for the WHL scoring title.<ref name="Canadian Gold"/><ref>{{cite web |title =Player of the Year - Four Broncos Memorial Trophy|url =http://whl.ca/records/awards.php?id=50|publisher =[[Western Hockey League|WHL]]|accessdate =2007-09-18}}</ref><ref name="Avalanche Website">{{Cite web|url=http://avalanche.nhl.com/team/app?page=PlayerDetail&playerId=8451101&service=page&tab=bio|title=Colorado Avalanche Team Bio|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=Colorado Avalanche|year=2006|author=Colorado Avalanche|authorlink=Colorado Avalanche}}</ref>

==NHL career==
===Quebec Nordiques===
Sakic was drafted 15th overall by the [[Quebec Nordiques]] in the [[1987 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref name="Recordbook"/> Rather than make the immediate jump, he told the Nordiques management he would prefer to spend the 1987&ndash;88 season in Swift Current to prepare for the NHL.<ref name="Legends of Hockey">{{Cite web|url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net:8080/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=11437|title=Joe Sakic Page|accessdate=2007-04-09|publisher=Legends of Hockey|year=2007|author=Legends of Hockey}}</ref> He made his NHL debut on [[October 6]], [[1988]] against the [[Hartford Whalers]] and scored an assist. His first NHL goal came two days later against goaltender [[Sean Burke]] of the [[New Jersey Devils]].<ref name="NHLPA Bio">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhlpa.com/WebStats/PlayerBiography.asp?ID=4934|title=NHLPA Player Bio|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=NHLPA|year=2007|author=National Hockey League Players Association|authorlink=National Hockey League Players Association}}</ref> During the season, he wore #88 because his preferred number, #19 was already taken by a teammate, [[Alain C<U+00F4>t<U+00E9> (1957)|Alain C<U+00F4>t<U+00E9>]].<ref name="Numbers">{{cite book  | last = Morrison | first = Scott | authorlink = Scott Morrison | title = Hockey Night in Canada By the Numbers: From 00 to 99 |publisher = Key Porter Books Ltd. | date = 2007  | location = Toronto  | pages = 232  |id = ISBN 978-1-552639-84-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title =1988-89 Quebec Nordiques|url =http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0000471989.html|publisher =The Internet Hockey Database|accessdate =2007-07-16}}</ref> He finished his rookie season with 62 points in 70 games.

In [[1989-90 NHL season|1989&ndash;90]], his second NHL season, Sakic was able to switch his number back to his familiar #19 (Alain C<U+00F4>t<U+00E9> had retired over the summer), and scored 102 points, which was ninth overall in the league. At the start of the next season, [[1990-91 NHL season|1990&ndash;91]], he was named [[Captain (hockey)|co-captain]] along with [[Steven Finn]] (Sakic was captain for home games, Finn for away games)<ref name="Steven Finn">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hockeydraftcentral.com/1984/84057.html|title=1984 NHL Entry Draft: Steven Finn|accessdate=2007-11-21|publisher=HockeyDraftCentral.com|year=2005|author=Hockey Draft Central}}</ref> and again passed the 100 point mark, improving to 109 points and sixth overall in the leauge, but would slip during [[1991-92 NHL season|1991&ndash;92]] to 94 points, partly as a result of missing eleven games. Early on in the season, Sakic showed some of his leadership qualities, even while [[Mike Hough]] was serving as captain, as he stood firm in the [[Eric Lindros]] holdout issue. With Lindros holding out against the Nordiques, who were one of the worst teams in league, Sakic commented, "We only want players here who have the passion to play the game. I'm tired of hearing that name. He's not here and there are a lot of others in this locker room who really care about the game."<ref name="GrowingUp"/> Lindros was traded a year later, ending the situation and bringing in a number of quality players, which vastly improved the Nordiques.<ref name="Lindros">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/futures/2006draft/lookback_91_053106.html|title=A look back: 1991|accessdate=2007-04-15|publisher=NHL.com|year=2006|author=Roarke, Shawn P.}}</ref> During their first four seasons with Joe Sakic, the Nordiques finished last place in the [[Northeast Division (NHL)|Northeast Division]] and last in the entire league for three straight years, from [[1988-89 NHL season|1989]] to [[1990-91 NHL season|1991]].<ref name="Recordbook"/>

Starting with the [[1992-93 NHL season|1992&ndash;93 NHL season]], Sakic became the sole captain of the franchise.<ref name="Recordbook"/> Under his leadership, the Nordiques made the playoffs for the first time in six years, and set a franchise record for wins and points in the process (since broken by the [[2000-01 NHL season|2001]] Colorado Avalanche team).<ref name="Recordbook"/> Sakic reached the 100 point plateau, the third time he did so in five years, by scoring 48 goals and 105 points in the regular season, and added another 6 points in the playoffs. His production went down slightly to 92 points in [[1993-94 NHL season|1993&ndash;94]] as the Nordiques failed to make the playoffs again. After missing part of the [[1994-95 NHL season|1994&ndash;95]] season due to the players being [[1994-95 NHL lockout|locked out]] by owners, Sakic was 8 points behind [[Jaromir Jagr]] for the scoring title with a fourth place finish, and helped the Nordiques win the division title, their first in six years.<ref name="Recordbook"/>

===Colorado Avalanche===
In June of 1995, the Quebec Nordiques announced that they had been sold and were leaving Quebec. At the start of the [[1995-96 NHL season|1995&ndash;96 NHL season]], the franchise moved to [[Denver, Colorado]] and was renamed the [[Colorado Avalanche]]. Sakic led the team to its first [[Stanley Cup]] championship, scoring 120 points in 82 regular season games and 34 points in 22 playoff games. He was awarded the [[Conn Smythe Trophy]] as the Most Valuable Player of the 1996 NHL playoffs. During the run for the cup, Sakic again proved himself to be an effective team leader. Although he had missed the playoffs in five of his first seven years in the NHL, and lacked any postseason experience, he scored 18 goals, including six game-winners, and 34 points. He was one goal off from the record for goals in a playoff year, and his game-winning goals established a new record.<ref name="1997 NHL Yearbook">{{cite book | last = National Hockey League  | title = 1997 NHL Yearbook | year = 1996 | publisher = Worldsport Properties | location = Toronto | pages = 232}}</ref> 

In the [[1996-97 NHL season|1996&ndash;97]] season, Sakic only played in 65 games due to a lacerated calf,<ref name="Rocky Mountain News">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/nhl/article/0,2777,DRMN_23920_5301508,00.html|title=Sakic lets game, NHL do talking|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=Rocky Mountain News|year=2007|author=Sadowski, Rick}}</ref> yet still managed to score 74 points as the Avalanche earned their first [[President's Trophy]] and third straight division title.<ref name="NHLPA Bio">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhlpa.com/WebStats/PlayerBiography.asp?ID=4934|title=NHLPA Player Bio|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=NHLPA|year=2007|author=National Hockey League Players Association|authorlink=National Hockey League Players Association}}</ref> He had another great playoff season with 8 goals and 17 assists, and took the Avalanche all the way to the conference finals, where they eventually lost to the [[Detroit Red Wings]] in six games. As a free agent during the summer of 1997, Sakic signed a three year, $21 million [[offer sheet]] with the [[New York Rangers]] as an unrestricted free agent. Under the collective bargaining agreement at the time, the Avalanche had one week to match the Rangers' offer or let go of Sakic. Colorado would match the offer,<ref name="Legends of Hockey"/> which instigated a salary raise for many NHL players.<ref name="TSN about the CBA">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=99378&hubname=nhl|title=Three key contracts helped kill the CBA|accessdate=2007-04-09|publisher=TSN.ca|year=2004|author=Associated Press}}</ref> 

Injuries would again limit Sakic's playing time in the [[1997-98 NHL season|1997&ndash;98]] season. While playing in his first Olympics with Team Canada, Sakic hurt his knee and was forced to miss eighteen games with the Avalanche.<ref name="Avalanche Website"/> In the sixty-four games he did play in, he still scored 63 points, enough to earn him his seventh All-Star appearance.<ref name="NHLPA Bio"/> He finally rebounded from his injury problems in the [[1998-99 NHL season|1998&ndash;99]] season, finishing fifth in the league in scoring with 41 goals and 96 points in only 73 games. He led the Avalanche all the way to within one game of the Stanley Cup finals, where they lost to the eventual Stanley Cup winning Dallas Stars. After the season ended, Sakic was ranked number 94 on ''[[The Hockey News]]''' list of the 100 Greatest Hockey Players.<ref name="100 Greatest Players">{{cite book | last = Dryden | first = Steve  | title = The Top 100 NHL Players Of All Time | year = 1997 | publisher = McClelland & Stewart Inc. | location = Toronto | pages = 160}}</ref>

During the [[1999-00 NHL season|1999&ndash;00]] season, Sakic reached several career milestones. Injuries limited him to only 60 games, but he still managed to lead the team in scoring with 81 points. On [[December 27]], [[1999]], against the [[St. Louis Blues (hockey)|St. Louis Blues]], Sakic earned an assist to become the 56th player in NHL history to reach 1,000 career points.<ref name="2001 NHL Yearbook"/> Later in the season, on [[March 23rd]], [[2000]], he scored a hat trick against the [[Phoenix Coyotes]], and became the 59th player to score 400 career goals.<ref name="2001 NHL Yearbook"/> It also gave him 1,049 points with the Quebec/Colorado franchise, passing [[Peter Stastny]] as the all-time leader on the team.<ref name="NHLPA Bio"/> Sakic eclipsed the 100 point mark again in [[2000-01 NHL season|2000&ndash;01]], finishing with 118 along with a career best 54 goals. He led the Avalanche to their second Stanley Cup championship, and won the [[Hart Memorial Trophy]], the [[Lady Byng Memorial Trophy]] and the [[Lester B. Pearson Award]]. After the Avalanche defeated the [[New Jersey Devils]] in the 2001 finals in seven games, Sakic received the cup first as the captain. But instead of hoisting it high, he passed it straight to [[Ray Bourque]], a player who had waited a record-breaking twenty-two seasons to win the Stanley Cup.<ref name="Pass">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=287897|title=A hockey tradition comes to the NFL|accessdate=2007-01-28|publisher=NHL.com|year=2007|author=Weiner, Evan}}</ref> The [[2001-02 NHL season|2001&ndash;02]] season saw Sakic lead the Avalanche in scoring again, finishing sixth in the league with seventy-nine points. On [[March 9]], [[2002]], he played in his 1,000th career game. The Avalanche once again reached the Western Conference Finals, but lost to the eventual Cup winning [[Detroit Red Wings]]. The following year Sakic appeared in only 58 games, and finished with just 58 points, the lowest total of his career.<ref name="NHLPA Bio"/> He rebounded the following year, finishing third in the league with 87 points. It also marked the first time since the [[1993-94 NHL season|1993&ndash;94]] season that his team did not win the division title, which was won by the [[Vancouver Canucks]].

[[Image:SakicWarmup1.JPG|left|thumb|250px|Sakic warming up before a game in 2007]] 

Following the [[2004-05 NHL lockout|2004&ndash;05 NHL lockout]], the Avalanche were forced to lose many of their key players in order to stay below the salary cap.<ref name="Lockout">{{Cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=2116068|title=Sakic, Blake to stay; Forsberg, Foote up in air|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=ESPN.com|year=2005|author=Associated Press}}</ref> Even with the loss of teammates [[Peter Forsberg]] and [[Adam Foote]], Sakic still helped the Avalanche get into the playoffs, where they eventually lost to the [[Anaheim Ducks]] in the conference semifinals. In June 2006, Sakic signed a one-year, $5.75 million deal to keep him with the Avalanche for the [[2006-07 NHL season|2006&ndash;07]] season.<ref name="Contract">{{Cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/avalanche/ci_3961182|title=Sakic stays with Avs|accessdate=2006-09-19|publisher=DenverPost.com|year=2006|author=Dater, Adrian}}</ref> Upon the retirement of [[Steve Yzerman]] a month later, on [[July 3]], [[2006]], Sakic became the league leader for most NHL career points scored among active players.

Sakic had another strong season in the [[2006-07 NHL season|2006&ndash;07]]. He scored his 600th career goal on [[February 15]], [[2007]], against the Calgary Flames, becoming the seventeenth player in history to reach the milestone and third that year.<ref name="600 Goals">{{Cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=270215003|title=Sakic scores empty-netter for No. 600 in Avs' win|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=ESPN.com|year=2007|author=Associated Press}}</ref> On the final day of the regular season, he scored his 100th point, reaching the milestone for the sixth time in his career.<ref name="100 Points">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?articleid=298738&page=NewsPage&service=page|title=Sakic signs 1-year deal with Avalanche|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=NHL.com|year=2007|author=Associated Press}}</ref> At the same time, Sakic became the second-oldest NHL player to score 100 points in a season at age 37, alongside hockey legend [[Gordie Howe]]. Despite his efforts as well as a late season charge, Sakic and the Avalanche missed the playoffs for the first time in eleven years, finishing one point behind the eighth placed Calgary Flames.

In April 2007, Sakic signed on for a 19th NHL season with the Colorado Avalanche, signing a one-year deal for the [[2007-08 NHL season|2007&ndash;08]] season.<ref name="Sakic signs one-year deal with Avalanche">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=203493&hubname=|title=Sakic signs one-year deal with Avalanche|accessdate=2007-04-09|publisher=TSN.ca|year=2007|author=Canadian Press}}</ref> Sakic commented on the deal, saying "at this stage in my career, I prefer to do one-year deals as I evaluate my play year-to-year."<ref name="Sakic signs one-year deal with Avalanche"/> Upon signing Sakic to the deal, Avalanche General Manager [[Francois Giguere]] said, "Joe is the heart of this organization and his leadership and value to this team and especially our young players is unquestioned."<ref name="Sakic resigned">{{Cite web|url=http://ottsun.canoe.ca/Sports/Hockey/2007/04/10/3970991-sun.html|title=Sakic reaches deal to return to Avs|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=Ottawa Sun|year=2007|author=Associated Press}}</ref> On [[May 1]], the NHL announced that Sakic was named as one of the three finalists of the Lady Byng Trophy,<ref name="Byng Finalist">{{Cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/sports/ci_5796168|title=Sakic one of three Lady Byng finalists|accessdate=2007-05-13|publisher=The Denver Post|year=2007|author=Dater, Adrian}}</ref> but it was eventually awarded to [[Pavel Datsyuk]] of the Detroit Red Wings.  On [[October 7]], [[2007]], he scored a goal and had an assist against the [[San Jose Sharks]], moving past [[Phil Esposito]] into eighth place on the NHL career points list with 1,591.<ref>{{cite news |title =Game Recap - Avalanche 6, Sharks 2|url =http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?service=page&page=Recap&gameNumber=35&season=20072008&gameType=2|author =[[Associated Press]]|publisher =[[NHL]]|date =[[2007-10-07]]|accessdate =2007-10-27}}</ref> Nineteen days later, Sakic scored a goal and assisted [[Ryan Smyth]] for an overtime game-winning goal against the Calgary Flames, reaching his 1,600th point in the NHL.<ref>{{cite news |title =Game Recap - Avalanche 3, Flames 2, OT|url =http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?service=page&page=Recap&gameNumber=144&season=20072008&gameType=2|author =[[Associated Press]]|publisher =[[NHL]]|date =[[2007-10-26]]|accessdate =2007-10-27}}</ref>

=== All-Star Games ===
Sakic has been voted into the [[NHL All-Star Game]] thirteen times and has played in twelve of them and was captain for two of them, most recently in 2007. He has at least one point in eleven of them.<ref>{{cite news |title =
Sakic Named To 13th NHL All-Star Game |url =http://avalanche.nhl.com/team/app?articleid=318937&page=NewsPage&service=page|author =|publisher =[[Colorado Avalanche]]|date =[[2007-01-09]]|accessdate =2007-02-19}}</ref> The only one that he missed entirely was the [[47th National Hockey League All-Star Game|1997 All-Star game]], due to an injury. Sakic won the Most Valuable Player award in the [[54th National Hockey League All-Star Game|2004 All-Star game]] after scoring a [[hat trick]] and leading the Western Conference to victory. He is the all-time assist leader in all-star games with 16 assists<ref name="AllStarAssists">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=287907|title=January 24, 2007 West's dozen goals does the trick|accessdate=2007-11-16|publisher=NHL.com|year=2007|author=Coffey, Phil}}</ref> and is third place in all-time all-star scoring with 22 points, behind [[Mario Lemieux]] (23 points) and [[Wayne Gretzky]] (25 points).<ref name="AllStarAssists"/> His best record in an All-Star game was in [[55th National Hockey League All-Star Game|2007]], when he scored four assists for the winning team; however the MVP award was given to [[Daniel Bri<U+00E8>re]], who had a goal and four assists<ref name="AllStarAssists"/>

