[[Image:Joe Sakic Team Canada.jpg|thumb|left|Sakic at the 2006 Olympics]]
Sakic has had an extensive international hockey career, having represented Canada at seven international competitions.<ref name="Canadian Gold"/> After being drafted by the Nordiques in 1987, he went on and helped Canada win the [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|1988 World Junior Championship]].<ref name="Legends of Hockey"/> His next tournament was the [[Ice Hockey World Championships|1991 World Championships]], where Canada won the silver medal and Sakic contributed eleven points in ten games.<ref name="Legends of Hockey"/> He tried out for the 1991 Canadian Canada Cup team, but was the first player to be cut, being cited for his weak leg strength.<ref name="Legends of Hockey"/> Sakic was bitter about the experience, feeling he wasn't given a good enough chance to prove himself, and called the whole experience "a complete waste of time."<ref name="Second Chance">{{cite news |title=Sakic's Second Chance|url=http://www.chl.ca/HockeyWorldCup/aug15_hkwc_sakic.html|author=Strachan, Al|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=[[1996-08-15]]|accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref>

Sakic's first successful professional tournament was the [[Ice Hockey World Championships|1994 World Championships]], where Canada won its first gold medal in the tournament since 1961. Sakic's seven points in eight games were a crucial part of the team's success.<ref name="Legends of Hockey"/> During the [[1996 World Cup of Hockey]], he played only a minor role in Canada's second place finish as he scored one goal and two assists in six games.<ref name="1996WCH">{{Cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/HockeyWorldCup/stats.html|title=1996 World Cup of Hockey Statistics|accessdate=2007-04-09|publisher=Canoe - Slam Sports!|year=1996|author=Canadian Press}}</ref> However the tournament allowed him to showcase that he was indeed a dominant player who had simply been overlooked.<ref name="HockeyWinner">{{Cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/HockeyWorldCup/sep16_wctucker.html|title=HOCKEY THE BIG WINNER|accessdate=2007-04-09|publisher=Canoe - Slam Sports!|year=1996|author=Tucker, Larry}}</ref>

Sakic's first Olympic appearance came in [[1998 Winter Olympics|1998]] at [[Nagano]], [[Japan]] after the event allowed NHL players to compete for the first time. Bothered by a knee injury, he only scored three points in four games,<ref name="Avalanche Website"/> as the Canadian squad failed to meet expectations and finished in fourth. Sakic's second Olympic appearance came in the [[2002 Winter Olympics]] in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]]. Led by his strong play, the Canadian team dominated all the way to the gold medal match against Team USA, where Sakic had four points and helped the team win its first gold medal in 50 years. He was later named MVP of the tournament with a cumulative tally of four goals and six assists. Sakic also played a part in Canada's triumph in the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], where he scored six points in six games.<ref name="Legends of Hockey"/>

On [[December 21]], [[2005]], Sakic was named captain of [[Canadian national men's hockey team|Team Canada]] for the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] in [[Turin]], [[Italy]].<ref name="USA Today">{{cite news |title=Canada's deep Olympic roster is minus Crosby|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/olympics/torino/hockey/2005-12-21-canada-roster_x.htm|author=Brehm, Mike|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=[[2005-12-21]]|accessdate=2007-11-19}}</ref> Once again, Team Canada was heavily favored and given high expectations, but they failed to medal, finishing seventh overall.<ref name="New York Times">{{cite news |title=2006 Olympic Winter Games -- HOckey: Men; Canada Is Left With Questions and Speculation|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01E2DF1F3EF937A15751C0A9609C8B63|author=Westhead, Rick|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=[[2006-02-24]]|accessdate=2007-11-19}}</ref> Sakic finished the tournament with three points.

==Personal life==
Sakic and his wife Debbie have three children: Mitchell and twins Chase and Kamryn.<ref name="Avalanche Website"/> They met at a local high school while he was playing in Swift Current, and they frequently return to the town during the off-season.<ref name="Denial of Death"/> Sakic is an avid golfer, and competed in the celebrity Pro Am golf tournament in [[Lake Tahoe]] in the Summer of 2006. Each Summer, he also hosts his own charity golf tournament which benefits the Colorado Food Bank.<ref name="Avalanche Website"/> His charity work, which is estimated to have provided more than 7 million meals to poor children and families, has earned an NHL Foundation Player Award in [[2007]].<ref>{{cite news |title =Sakic receives NHL Foundation Player Award for outstanding community service|url =http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?articleid=340142&page=NewsPage&service=page|publisher =[[NHL]]|date =[[2007-10-15]]|accessdate =2007-10-19}}</ref>

In his hometown of Burnaby, Sakic is a fan favourite, and even has a street named "Joe Sakic Way" in his honour.<ref name="No Average Joe"/> Throughout [[British Columbia]] he is affectionately known as "Burnaby Joe";<ref name="ESPN Page 2">{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/page2/s/bermanfiles/sakicresponses.html|title=Case No. 4, Joe Sakic
|accessdate=2007-11-07|publisher=ESPN|year=2001|author=ESPN Page 2 Staff}}</ref> in [[Colorado]], he is known simply as "Super Joe."<ref name="nicknames"/> His younger brother [[Brian Sakic|Brian]] was a member of the same [[Swift Current Broncos]] during Joe's final season. He was drafted into the NHL, but did not play in the league. He did, however, play for the [[Flint Generals]] of the [[United Hockey League]].<ref name="Avalanche Website"/>

