==Legacy==
===Milestones===
Sakic recorded his 1000th career point on [[December 27]], [[1999]] against the [[St. Louis Blues (hockey)|St. Louis Blues]].<ref name="2001 NHL Yearbook">{{cite book | last = National Hockey League  | title = 2001 NHL Yearbook | year = 2000 | publisher = Worldsport Properties | location = Toronto | pages = 272}}</ref> He became the eleventh player to reach 1500 points, doing so on [[October 25]], [[2006]] with an assist against the [[Washington Capitals]], and the sixth to do so with one franchise.<ref name="1500 Points">{{Cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=2638889|title=Sakic scores 1,500th point|accessdate=2007-05-13|publisher=ESPN|year=2006|author=Associated Press}}</ref> [[Gordie Howe]], [[Wayne Gretzky]], [[Mario Lemieux]], [[Raymond Bourque]] and [[Steve Yzerman]] are the others who have achieved this feat.<ref name="No Average Joe"/>

Sakic played his 1000th career game on [[March 9]], [[2002]] against the [[Los Angeles Kings]].<ref name="Recordbook">{{cite book  | last = National Hockey League  | authorlink = National Hockey League  | title = National Hockey League Official Guide & Record Book 2007  |publisher = Dan Diamond & Associates, Inc.  | date = 2006  | location = Toronto  | pages = 656  |id = ISBN 978-1-894801-02-7}}</ref> His 500th career goal came against the [[Vancouver Canucks]] on [[December 11]], [[2002]].<ref name="500 Goals">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2002/12/11/sakic021211.html|title=Canucks spoil Sakic's 500th goal|accessdate=2007-11-07|publisher=CBC|year=2006|author=CBC Sports}}</ref> In a [[February 15]], [[2007]] game against the [[Calgary Flames]], Sakic scored his 600th career goal. He also earned his 900th assist, the sixteenth player to do so, against the Flames, in a game on [[March 12]], [[2006]]. <ref name="NHL Bio"/>

During the final game of the [[2006-07 NHL season|2006&ndash;07]] season, Sakic scored his 100th point of the year. This made him, at age 37, the second oldest player in NHL history, after Gordie Howe, to record 100 points in a regular season.<ref name="Forbes Article"/> He is the only captain in Colorado Avalanche history and became the longest active tenured captain in the league, with fifteen seasons leading the Nordiques/Avalanche franchise, after the retirement of Steve Yzerman at the conclusion of the 2005&ndash;06 regular season. <ref name="NHL Bio"/>

Alongside [[Bobby Clarke]], [[Wayne Gretzky]], and [[Mark Messier]], Sakic is one of four players to captain his team to a Stanley Cup championship and win the Hart Memorial Trophy in the same year. <ref name="Trophy Winner">{{Cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/NHLAwards/010615_awards1-sun.html|title=Sakic is no ordinary Joe|accessdate=2007-05-14|publisher=NBCSports.com|year=2001|author=Zeisberger, Mike}}</ref> Sakic is also one of nineteen members in the [[Triple Gold Club]], a term used in ice hockey to describe players who have won an Olympic Gold medal, a World Championship Gold medal and the Stanley Cup. <ref name="Triple Gold">{{Cite web|url=http://live82.ihwc.net/english/article/news/index.ihwc?&artId=2646|title=IIHF announces NHL-European Victoria Cup|accessdate=2007-05-13|publisher=IHWC.net|year=2007|author=IHWC.NET staff}}</ref>

===Records===
In his 18-year career with the Nordiques and Avalanche, Sakic has obtained nearly all of the franchise scoring records, including most all-time goals (610), assists (979), and points (1579). He also holds the franchise record for most games played (1,319),<ref name="Recordbook"/> and is on several notable NHL record lists:

<div style="float:left; margin-right:1.5em;">

{{h4|All-time}}

* 1st place <U+2013> Most points of active players (1589)
* 1st place <U+2013> All-Star game assists (16)
* 3rd place <U+2013> All-Star game points (22)
* 9th place <U+2013> Most points<ref name="Forbes Article">{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/04/09/ap3592898.html|title=Sakic Reaches 100 Points As Avs Win|accessdate=2007-04-10|publisher=Associated Press|year=2007|author=Stapleton, Arnie}}</ref>
* 11th place <U+2013> Most assists (979)
* 14th place <U+2013> Most goals (610)
</div><div style="float:left; margin-right:1.5em;">
{{h4|Playoffs}}
* 1st place <U+2013> Most overtime goals (7)<ref name="NBC Article">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcsports.com/nhl/1457080/detail.html|title=NHL playoffs by the numbers: Goal-happy|accessdate=2007-05-14|publisher=NBCSports.com|year=2007|author=Schiazza, Brian}}</ref>
* 2nd place <U+2013> Most goals in single season (18, in 1995&ndash;96)<ref name="1997 NHL Yearbook"/>
</div><br clear="all">

===Leadership===
Throughout his career, Sakic has been one of the top scorers in the league, but was widely criticized for not leading his team to any playoff success.<ref name="100 Greatest Players"/> While in Quebec, the Nordiques were one of the worst teams in the league, finishing last in their division five out of the seven years Sakic was with the team, including three straight years of being last overall in the league.<ref name="Recordbook"/> After leading the Avalanche to the Stanley Cup in 1996 with his 34 points, Sakic began to be seen as a leader capable of winning, and he was seen as one of the league's premier players.<ref name="Recognition">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chl.ca/HockeyWorldCup/sep5_sakic.html|title=Sakic gets what's coming to him|accessdate=2007-11-25|publisher=Canadian Hockey League|year=1996|author=Canadian Press}}</ref>

Though Sakic is a quiet individual, he is able to motivate his team to play at higher levels, which has earned him the respect of his peers and executives.<ref name="Captain">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2001/06/09/stanleyfinal010609.html|title=Captains Sakic, Stevens are consummate hockey leaders|accessdate=2007-11-26|publisher=CBC|year=2001|author=Stevens, Neil}}</ref> The first signs of Sakic's leadership began to show while still a member of the Swift Current Broncos of the WHL. After the bus crash that killed four of his teammates, Sakic was seen as the leader of the team, acknowledging that the experiance changed his outlook on life. This was further proven during the summer of 1997 when the New York Rangers offered him a large contract, in order to replace captain [[Mark Messier]] (who had left the team for the Vancouver Canucks), which under the rules of the NHL, the Avalanche were able to match.<ref name="TSN about the CBA"/>

One of the most defining actions of Sakic's career was at the conclusion of the 2001 playoffs. Defying the NHL tradition of the captain being the first to skate around with the Stanley Cup, Sakic passed it off to teammate [[Ray Bourque]].<ref name="Bourque">{{cite news |title =Avalanche beat Devils to capture Stanley Cup|url =http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/cup01/games/2001-06-09-njcol.htm|author =Allen, Kevin|publisher =[[USA Today]]|date =[[2001-06-10]]|accessdate =2007-11-26}}</ref> Bourque, one of the best defencemen to ever play, had been traded to the Avalanche the year before after spending 21 years with the [[Boston Bruins]] and setting the record for most games played without winning the Cup.<ref name="Bourque Wins">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=290833|title=For Bourque, at long last Stanley!|accessdate=2007-11-26|publisher=NHL.com|year=2007|author=Roarke, Shawn P.}}</ref> Sakic's handing of the trophy to Bourque is seen as just another example of Sakic's leadership abilities and how he perfoms through actions rather than words.<ref name="Captain"/>

